|IGN=8.4<ref name=IGNreview>{{cite web|url=http://au.pc.ign.com/articles/161/161322p1.html |title=Finally, a driving game that will make your console-owning friends jealous.|publisher=[[IGN]]|author=Tal Blevins|date=[[June 11]] [[1999]]|accessdate=2008-06-18}}</ref>
|PCZone=9.0<ref name=PCZreview>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=3199|date=[[August 13]] [[2001]] |title=Midtown Madness|publisher=''[[PC Zone]]''|accessdate=2008-06-18}}</ref>
|GSpot=7.7<ref name=GSpotreview>{{cite web|url=http://au.gamespot.com/pc/driving/midtownmadness/review.html |title=Midtown Madness for PC review|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|author=[[Greg Kasavin]]|date=[[May 27]] [[1999]]|accessdate=2008-06-18}}</ref>
|rev1=Total Video Games
|rev1Score=7/10<ref name=TVG>{{cite web|url=http://www.totalvideogames.com/articles/Midtown_Madness_Chicago_Edition_229.htm |title=Midtown Madness: Chicago Edition Review|author=Noel Brady|publisher=Total Video Games|date=[[January 12]] [[2000]]|accessdate=2008-07-12}}</ref>
|GR=81%<ref name=GameRankings>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/htmlpages2/907330.asp |title=Midtown Madness - PC|publisher=[[Game Rankings]]|accessdate=2008-06-18}}</ref>
|MBR=84/100<ref name=MobyRank>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobygames.com/game/windows/midtown-madness/mobyrank |title=Midtown Madness for Windows|publisher=[[MobyGames]]|accessdate=2008-07-12}}</ref>
}}
Reception of the game has generally been positive. [[IGN]] rated game's appearance highly, noting that overall "the downtown portion of Chicago is portrayed very accurately", though generic looking portions of the city were noted.<ref name=IGNreview /> [[GameSpot]] approved of the variety in third person, first person dashboard, and widescreen driving views. However, it complained of the game suffering from "choppy frame rates" and unconvincing effects.<ref name=GSpotreview /> ''[[PC Zone]]'' praised Angel Studios for avoiding gimmicks, but instead presenting "accurately modelled cars and a meticulously recreated city" to the player.<ref name=PCZreview /> [[Allgame]] said ''Midtown Madness'' "possesses superb, immersive graphics", noting the changing times of day and weather. However, it noted that non-player cars were lacking in details.<ref name=Allgame /> ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' said that as well as being "structurally and visually consistent", the Chicago setting in ''Midtown Madness'' was "brought to life".<ref name=CVGreview /> Total Video Games, however, called the game's presentation "far from optimal" even at the recommended [[system requirements]]. The reviewer pointed out a "a serious lack of detail" and blockiness, especially without a [[graphics card]].<ref name=TVG />

[[Image:Midtown madness screenshot.jpg|left|thumb|A heavily damaged [[Cadillac Eldorado]] hitting oncoming traffic while being pursued by a [[police car]]. [[GameSpot]]'s [[Greg Kasavin]] praised the game for moments like this, stating "it's fun to be able to drive like a maniac...because you know you can't in real life".<ref name=GSpotreview />]]
IGN described in-game narration by [[Marty Lennartz]] as a nice touch, but noted some [[glitch]]es among the otherwise "distinctive engine and horn sounds".<ref name=IGNreview /> GameSpot called the game's sounds exceptional, with its variety of car noises such as the "warning beeps when the bus goes in reverse".<ref name=GSpotreview /> ''PC Zone'' praised the in-game radio system, and the support for external media players.<ref name=PCZreview /> Allgame said players "get a dose of reality" with other drivers and pedastrians "hurling insults and exclamations your way",<ref name=Allgame /> while ''Computer and Video Games'' pointed out that a "city bus legitimately pulling out at a four-way junction can end your attempt instantly and tragically."<ref name=CVGreview /> Total Video Games was critical of the setting, arguing that it felt as if cars "are often driving without noticing you at all".<Ref name=TVG />

Reviews of ''Midtown Madness'' attributed most praise to its gameplay or "fun" elements. IGN wrote the game "doesn't rely heavily on driving authenticity; this game's all about fun", praising the simplicity whereby players can "pick a real-world car and go".<ref name=IGNreview /> GameSpot wrote "it's fun to be able to drive like a maniac...because you know you can't in real life."<ref name=GSpotreview />  ''Computer and Video Games'' said the game contained humor aspects, provided by other drivers, police, contenders (described as maniacs), and the "carnage that unfolds before your windscreen".<ref name=CVGreview /> ''PC Zone'' recommended the game, calling it highly refreshing, while Total Video Games said the game seemed a good choice, but suggested that it would be outdone by [[GT Interactive]]'s ''[[Driver (video game)|Driver]]'', released soon after.<ref name=TVG /> Allgame called it a "must-buy for the driving game enthusiast", and argued it would appeal to those who were not otherwise fans of the genre.<ref name=Allgame />

